values.text: $name your symptoms do not suggest that you have COVID-19. Continue following the common measures and government directives to avoid contracting COVID-19. Remember that your symptoms may also result from other diseases and may require medical consultation - this interview targets the COVID-19 infection. If your symptoms seem severe and you are worried, contact your doctor or local health authorities.

What should you do?

1)Take preventive measures:
Since you have no symptoms that may suggest COVID-19 and you have not been in contact with a confirmed or probable case of COVID-19 disease, there is little reason to suspect that you are currently infected. You do not need to seek medical consultation, contacting local authorities nor quarantine; however, we strongly recommend taking preventative measures, strictly following your regional public authority guidelines.

2)Maintain strict hygiene:
It is strongly recommended for you to take simple precautions that can reduce your chances of being infected in the future or spreading the virus:
Regularly and thoroughly clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water for at least 20 seconds

3)Avoid touching eyes, nose and mouth
Cover your mouth and nose with your bent elbow or tissue when you cough or sneeze
Disinfect your hands after sneezing.
Do not share your cups, plates, cutlery, and other household utensils with family members.

4)Maintain social distancing
Social/physical distancing is critical to stopping COVID-19 transmission. Maintain a distance of at least 1 meter (3 feet) between yourself and others, even if they are not exhibiting symptoms of COVID-19.

5)Avoid public places ‚Äì especially if you are an older person or have a condition such as diabetes, heart, or lung disease.

6)Monitor your health
You are strongly advised to regularly use this diagnostic tool, particularly should your circumstances change, such as the occurrence of new symptoms or contact with an infected person.
Your answers do not suggest that you have the COVID-19. However, your symptoms are worrisome and require medical consultation.

What should you do?

1)Call a doctor or healthcare facility
Call your GP in advance and tell him or her about your symptoms. The doctor will ask you about your current complaints and medical history, and he or she may decide to invite you to come in for a check-up. If your symptoms seem very severe, suddenly get worse, and you are worried, go to your nearest Emergency Department (call in advance if possible) or call an emergency number.

2)When should you call 102 or your local emergency number?

3)Wash your hands often
Your hands are a carrier for the coronavirus. Every time you touch your face area, cough into your palms, or go to the toilet, your hands become contaminated and spread the virus to everything you come into contact with. It is crucial, for the safety of your household members, that you clean your hands regularly with soap and water or an alcohol-based rub.

values.text: Your symptoms are very serious and you may have COVID-19.

What should you do?

1)Immediately separate yourself from other people and animals in your house:
If possible, isolate yourself in a separate room, away from other members of your household. If this is not possible, keep a distance of at least 1 meter from others and wear a protective surgical mask. Avoid all interaction with household pets.

2)Call the emergency number:
Call the emergency number (102). Your symptoms are severe and you may need to be transported to a medical facility.

3)Wear a surgical face mask:
Put on a surgical face mask whenever somebody is about to enter the same room or vehicle as you. Put on a surgical face mask before entering an ambulance or medical facility. People interacting with you should wear face masks as well, particularly if you have difficulty breathing.
